The 'bee car' that avoids collisions
In order to advance the development of technologies for accident prevention, Nissan has been inspired, this time, by nature, especially by bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, by imitating the theft of bees, avoids accidents.
It is called Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C and represents the first steps towards collision prevention technologies.
The engineers at Nissan Motor Co.’s Advanced Technical Center developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Development of Brand Management, the BR23C represents the growth of Nissan’s security shield.
This robot will allow the brand’s vehicles to prevent collisions.
During its flight, each bee creates its own personal space of an oval shape that looks a lot like the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important are the bee’s composite eyes, capable of seeing at an angle of more than 300 degrees and in all directions, allowing it to fly uninterruptedly inside its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, the engineers developed what is called a laser range finder.
It detects the obstacles that are at a distance of two meters and within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to this object and sends a signal to the microprocessor, immediately, to avoid the obstacle.
"As soon as it detects an obstacle, the little robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by forging its wheels 90 degrees or more to avoid collision.
The biggest difference from any other existing system is that the evasion maneuver is totally instinctive.
If that were the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Moving Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be diverted up or down, nor diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and according to what its wheels allow it and not in infinite directions like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, but also acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid obstacles.
"Every second this device must only process information and act on that data.
It does not need to keep the information or intuitive logics of previous manoeuvres, so it can run continuously with only a few dozen KB of memory.
It may come as a surprise, but we’re not talking about gigabytes of memory, not even megabytes.”
This represents the first car to develop new technologies for instant collision prevention, a technology that will be introduced into standard cars in a decade, according to Nissan.
The robot works with lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible application of this technology in the future could be the adaptation of this device to a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to its destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
