A week after revealing an interim deal, the two banks explained that MUFG would buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley’s ordinary shares at a unit price of $25.25, or a total amount of $3 billion.
The deducted price is 19% lower than the book value of the securities at 31 August.
MUFG will invest an additional $6 billion in the acquisition of convertible securities with a yield of 10% and a conversion price of $31.25.
Morgan Stanley said the overall transaction would be based on an average unit price of $29, which is 28% above its current price.
Morgan Stanley's stock, however, lost 6.79% to $23.07 by 17:00 GMT.
“This strategic alliance is an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to banking holding status,” said John Mack, the group’s CEO.
Morgan Stanley adopted this new statute last week, which should allow him to diversify his activities but puts him under the authority of the Federal Reserve.
His alliance with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis forces the biggest Wall Street names to adopt a much more cautious attitude than before.
The terms presented on Monday also show that the deal has been changed in recent days: last Monday, Morgan had simply announced that he would sell up to 20% of his shares to Japan for about $8.5 billion.
“A week ago,” Toshihide Mizuno, MUFG’s chief executive, explained in Tokyo, “we thought the participation would be entirely made up of ordinary shares.
But given the current situation of the economy and the market, we wanted to minimize the risks and cover ourselves.”
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will pay its Morgan Stanley securities 7% below their book value.
And the operation will result in a dilution of about 20% of the profit per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert within one year half of its preferred securities into ordinary shares if they trade more than 50% above the conversion price, or at about $47, over a given period.
Morgan Stanley assures that MUFG’s capital will allow it to seize investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its liquidity.
A group spokeswoman, however, refused to provide details on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
Following MUFG’s investment, Morgan Stanley is expected to show a Tier One solvency ratio of around 15%, one of the best in the sector.
Morgan said he had “slightly” lightened his balance sheet since the end of August.
The last few weeks have been stressful for the group, which saw its stock market price melt by half as the cost of insurance against a risk of default on its debt went away.
The cost dropped on Monday but remained at a high level, around 12%.
Last week, Goldman Sachs, the only other “survivor” of Wall Street’s major investment banks after the bankruptcy of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the acquisition of Merrill Lynch, announced it had raised $15 billion, partly from Berkshire Hathaway, Warren Buffett’s group.
Rafael Correa in Quito on Monday.
Re-founding the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like its counterparts and friends, it was the third one that put to the vote a draft new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since 64% of voters voted "yes" to the referendum, according to official results covering 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" obtained 28%, 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% were white votes.
For the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to get half of the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the exit of polling stations and a countdown from a non-governmental organization announced a broad "yes" victory, ranging from 63% to 70%.
Rafael Correa claimed in the night from Sunday to Monday the victory of his draft Constitution.
The “Constitution has triumphed overwhelmingly,” he had assured, congratulating the Ecuadorians at the headquarters of the governorate of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez and Morales but also his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which took place calmly according to the Observation Mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), focused on a 444-point text consolidating the "new socialism" defended by the president.
The draft Constitution dedicates the power of the state to the economy, preserving it with the "development planning" of a country living mainly from the extraction of oil by foreign companies and the currencies sent by its immigrants.
Powered by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants strengthened powers to the head of state, who will be able to carry out up to two consecutive four-year terms and will have the opportunity to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and hold a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution further consolidates the principle of the free provision of health and education services that the President began to introduce in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for U.S. anti-drug operations.
19 hostages released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the assault on the kidnappers of the 11 tourists and their eight escorts captured ten days ago.
They are in Cairo.
The 11 European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts held captive for ten days in the desert were brought back safely and soundly to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they were released by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
Apparently in shape, the hostages arrived at about 3:30 p.m. aboard a special plane at al-Maza military base, which was escorted to Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred, unable to speak to the press, on board helicopters to the Maadi hospital, a residential suburb of Cairo, for examinations.
They are in “good health,” and “no ransom was paid” to the kidnappers,” Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna said on the tarmac.
Captured on September 19 during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been balloted from one cache to another by 35 unknown abductors.
It includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the safari agency Aegyptous.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, carrying two helicopters, had launched the attack the night before dawn.
"There was an exchange of gunfire, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others fleeing," the official said.
He said 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "flash" unit had been sent to Sudan, where they received the support of German and Italian commandos.
The head of Italian diplomacy Franco Frattini mentioned from Belgrade, where he is, the role played by secret agents and elements of Italian special forces.
"We have to recognize that we have achieved this result through the professionalism and efficiency of our secret service men, special forces," he said, without further details.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted during a patrol a 4x4 vehicle on which the kidnappers were aboard, killing six, including the Chadian leader, and arresting two.
The army had claimed that they were linked to a rebel group from Darfur, the Sudan-Unity Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which the movement had immediately denied.
