Benelux Governments Nationalize Part of Fortis Bank
The Benelux states come to the aid of the Belgian-Dutch bank, as the first European banking institution in distress as a result of the snowball effect of the credit market crisis in the United States, by partially nationalizing it. The three countries also support interest, in the amount of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>11.2 billion in Hongrias and these institutions.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourgish and Dutch governments agreed, at the highest level, on this matter, by also appealing to the European Central Bank and the European Commission's competition officer.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the international financial crisis intensifying for more than a year is for Fortis Bank. From a certain point of view, the decisions that will be taken in the case of this bank will serve as a precedent.
According to the decision made on Sunday night, the three states will buy back nearly half (up to 49%) of the bank’s capital located in each of the countries.
The bank will undoubtedly sell some of its shares, including, first of all, the activities, mainly insurance, which it acquired last year from the Dutch agency ABN Amro.
Last week, Fortis stocks began a dizzying fall. In the second half of the week, serious signs of crisis have already been revealed at the bank.
Analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is far too big to let go of bankruptcy.
On Friday alone, the company’s shares fell 12 percent, reaching its lowest level 14 years ago.
Since January, stocks have fallen by more than two-thirds of their value.
Taking into account the current value of the shares, the total value of the group's capital is around 14 billion euros, which, according to the company's leaders, is not realistic.
The management of the company accuses the uncertainty of overseas, in connection with the adoption of the US $700 billion bailout plan, of being the cause of the fall of Fortis stocks.
On Monday, the paperwork had already benefited from a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the bank’s new CEO.
The financial institution was also looking for private buyers, but has not yet received a proposal on the merits.
Previously, the Belgian government announced that investors should not worry, they were not going to lose their money.
There was no panic in the bank’s clientele circle, and no agency was assaulted.
In Hungary, Fortis owns independent agencies and has also acquired leasing companies.
A fox in the chicken house
In America, life and health insurance companies often refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate, based on information about their drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programs that link the use of information relating to the prescription of medicines, in any case, to the consent of the person concerned.
This kind of program has to be in independent hands, otherwise it’s about assigning its chicken to a fox,” Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage prescription drugs, told The Washington Post.
Insurance companies rely on the insurance premium and the insured capital in the event of damage, on the client’s state of health, and if they feel the risk is too high, they don’t even insure it.
In the past, they sent the candidates for a medical examination, and they only signed an insurance contract with them after learning of the results.
For ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, he easily provides himself with pharmacies, data about the person's drug purchases in the past eighteen months. From this, the program determines himself, what health he or she is suffering from.
For example, if this person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol reducer, it refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately puts him in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some at the same time determine a risk coefficient, so there is not much left to do to the insurer except the paperwork. However, small problems may still appear.
Among the disadvantages of this program is the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes. For example, some mixtures can be used against migraine or heatstroke, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while the others do not.
Companies have grown in data research and analysis, and they need to ask the patient for permission before collecting the necessary information from the pharmacy.
From now on, they are forced by the authorities, even if they have not been sanctioned for their failures in the past.
Recently, some companies have also been processing the results of laboratory tests, linking them with data on drug consumption, and thus being able to provide an even more accurate picture of patients' health status.
More and more companies have access to data, and control of usage is becoming increasingly difficult at the same time.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A bill to expand the authorities' control circle on companies specializing in the provision of data is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not enough and that is why he has further developed his program, which would condition the transmission of data to the exclusive agreement of the person concerned.
It is another question of whether the person concerned is really free to give their consent or not, because if they refuse, insurance does not sign an insurance contract with them.
Thus, and ultimately, the chickens depend on the kindness of the fox.
The global menu of Marseille
The European Union and India are doubling their trade.
Since the European Union and India are very important trading partners for each other, this theme also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit alongside other problems, largely global.
Today, there will also be a France-India summit where it will be mainly about cooperation in the field of atomic energy.
The European Union recognises that India is a major emerging democratic power that should be given a broader voice in international affairs, but member countries have not yet managed to agree on their support in New Delhi for its candidacy as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
They did not get too caught up in this issue yesterday at this 9th summit in Marseille.
The French President, Nicolas Sarkozy, as the current President of the Union, as well as the President of the Commission José Manuel Barroso and the head of diplomacy, Javier Solana, welcomed the Prime Minister of India, Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed that in a hundred years, they were going to multiply by one thousand, two times as many as exchanges.
Considering that between 2000 and 2007, trade in goods has increased from $25 billion to $55 billion, this does not seem to be an overly ambitious goal.
In this sense, they have legally harmonized the 26 bilateral conventions with India on civil flights, so that air traffic can also grow in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the EU by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy has promised to speed up negotiations.
The aim is to balance the situation with, on the one hand, India, which is the EU's first trading partner, and, on the other hand, New Delhi, which only ranks ninth among the EU's partners.
The summit devoted its attention to global affairs.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan has been strongly condemned, as well as all forms of terrorism, and the urgent need for a United Nations conference on this topic has been raised.
The completion of the Doha trade cycle has also been called for, although both have a large share in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed that it remains true to the energy and climate programme, in particular that it would like to reduce its releases of toxic substances by at least 20 percent by 2020.
India also agreed on this point, as well as with the fact that a global market should be held at the climate conference scheduled next year, and to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by fifty percent by 2050.
They would also like to prevent rising food prices, and have supported the convening of an international working meeting to address the financial crisis.
The Indian head of state is on a visit to the French capital, where he is preparing to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of atomic energy at a bilateral meeting.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive orders worth twenty billion euros for the construction of Indian nuclear reactors.
According to the news agency, the deal would last for 15 years.
