Found Steve Fossett's plane, the billionaire who disappeared a year ago.
The wreckage of Steve Fosset's plane, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, was found.
The debris was found on a plateau at an altitude of 3,000 metres, in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammonth Lakes, on the California-Nevada border.
Inside the plane, however, no human remains.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson has cleared the remaining doubts: “The plane was located, we sent a team, and now we have confirmation that this is the one Steve Fosset was traveling on the day he disappeared,” he said at a press conference.
The sheriff said that no human remains were found either on the plane or in the vicinity.
In February, the 63-year-old billionaire was considered dead.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Bureau (NTSB) said that a few hours after the wreckage was spotted, a team of investigators sent to the scene identified the aircraft: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, which disappeared on September 3, 2007, when Fosset took off from Yerington to Nevada.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fosset’s personal belongings were found by a couple around their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents bearing the name of Fosset, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a pullover.
Fossett's research was interrupted a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had earned a place in history thanks to a long set of records.
At the sixth attempt, he became in 2002, the first man to complete the world tour on an aerostatic balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later, he toured the world by plane and without a stopover.
Among all these records, also the one to have flown at 15,445 meters high, on the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
